{"action":"created","issue":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/20","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/20/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/20/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/20/events","html_url":"https://github.com/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/20","id":1234309865,"node_id":"I_kwDODx3ZIc5JkhLp","number":20,"title":"Exploration of native parquet predicate pushdown support with arrow-native geometries","user":{"login":"kylebarron","id":15164633,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjE1MTY0NjMz","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/15164633?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron","html_url":"https://github.com/kylebarron","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/kylebarron/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":10,"created_at":"2022-05-12T17:55:37Z","updated_at":"2022-05-13T00:28:00Z","closed_at":"2022-05-12T21:02:45Z","author_association":"NONE","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"This came up in a couple comments ([1](https://github.com/opengeospatial/geoparquet/issues/1#issuecomment-1090676109), [2](https://github.com/opengeospatial/geoparquet/issues/13#issuecomment-1124426703)) in [geoparquet](https://github.com/opengeospatial/geoparquet) and just wanted to bring it up here.

The current geometry representation under discussion is a [logical nested list representation](https://github.com/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/pull/12). One issue is that in Parquet this representation is stored as a [single native list](https://github.com/opengeospatial/geoparquet/issues/13#issuecomment-1124079735). This means that the Parquet min/max statistics apply over both `x` **and** `y`, and can't be used for spatial filtering. However an Arrow `StructArray` with `x` and `y` separated [does get stored](https://github.com/opengeospatial/geoparquet/issues/13#issuecomment-1124232173) as two distinct columns in the underlying Parquet, with two separate statistics items.

So the main question here is: should we consider a `StructArray` approach in geo-arrow? Is there any way with the nested list approach to have them stored as two different physical columns in Parquet so as to make use of Parquet's predicate pushdown support?","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/20/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/20/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null},"comment":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/comments/1125541965","html_url":"https://github.com/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/20#issuecomment-1125541965","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/20","id":1125541965,"node_id":"IC_kwDODx3ZIc5DFmhN","user":{"login":"paleolimbot","id":10995762,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEwOTk1NzYy","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/10995762?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot","html_url":"https://github.com/paleolimbot","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2022-05-13T00:28:00Z","updated_at":"2022-05-13T00:28:00Z","author_association":"NONE","body":"I've always liked the struct approach better than than the interleaved xy[zm]...it feels more "Arrow-like" to me for reasons precisely like this one. There's also no reason the spec can't support both (i.e., the "geoarrow.point" extension type can have more than one storage type). I'm planning to move some of the C++ I've been working with into its own repo in the next few days and will add back in struct reading and writing so that we everyone can properly experiment!","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/comments/1125541965/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}

{"action":"opened","number":22,"pull_request":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/pulls/22","id":948555255,"node_id":"PR_kwDODx3ZIc44ic33","html_url":"https://github.com/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/pull/22","diff_url":"https://github.com/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/pull/22.diff","patch_url":"https://github.com/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/pull/22.patch","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/geopandas/geo-arrow-spec/issues/22","number":22,"state":"open","locked":false,"title":"First draft specification for ARROW:extension:name and ARROW:extension:type metadata (i.e., ExtensionType definitions)","user":{"login":"paleolimbot","id":10995762,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEwOTk1NzYy","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/10995762?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot","html_url":"https://github.com/paleolimbot","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/paleolimbot/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"body":"This PR is an attempt to formalize how the memory layout described in #12 should be annotated with Array-level metadata to facilitate passing Arrays among computational tools/Arrow-aware file formats like Feather and Parquet. Concrete examples of files written using this draft metadata specification can be found in the prototype geoarrow R package (https://github.com/paleolimbot/geoarrow/tree/master/inst/example_feather) and the geoarrow-data repository (https://github.com/paleolimbot/geoarrow-data/).

